events.name: The cabbage Salon: The Self...and Other Drgs · Luma
events.description:
https://lu.ma/43m8iiy5

​The cabbage Salon is a space for curious minds, deep discussions, and unexpected connections. Each gathering brings people together to engage with big ideas—guided by a speaker, and shaped by the thoughts, experiences, and perspectives of everyone in the room.

​No academic background required—just a willingness to think, share, and listen.

​This salon is inspired by the texts of Johann Gottlieb Fichte, Thomas Nagel, Max Horkheimer, Theodor W. Adorno, and Robert Nozick.*

​The Self…

​We take for granted that each of us has a self—an “I.” The “I” in “I see the tree” or “I like this band.” But if we take a closer look, the “I”, that we are, becomes strangely elusive: If we try to focus on our pure “I”—stripped of any thought beyond the self-aware “I”—it slips from our grasp. The closer we try to get to it, the further it moves away. Trippy! What can we learn from philosophy about the nature of the self?

​...and Other Drgs**

​What are we seeking when we take mind-altering substances? The list of possible answers is long: self-improvement, self-destruction, self-purification... Do we seek liberation, community, chaos, or the unknown? None of the above? And what if there were a drg—inexpensive, free from side effects—that simply made us happier? Should we take it? Why—or why not? 

​Presented By:

​Georg Spoo, PhD. is an Assistant Professor of Philosophy, who practiced his Postdoc at Columbia University. His academic research focus is on epistemology, social and political philosophy, and existentialism. He currently consults with companies to incorporate philosophical ideas into the practical business world. Teams have benefitted from Georg’s discussions on the philosophy of decision-making so they’re equipped to make better ones. At the heart of Georg’s beliefs is that everyone should live in peace, and no one should have to suffer inequality.

​How We Do Things:

​🔹 Warm-Up: We start with a short icebreaker to get minds moving and ideas flowing.
🔹 Talk & Discussion: Our guest speaker introduces the theme, sharing insights and questions to consider.
🔹 Group Conversations: Attendees break into small groups to explore the topic, bringing their own ideas and experiences into the mix.
🔹 More Talk, More Conversation: Our speaker presents a second round of thoughts, deepening the discussion before another round of open dialogue.
🔹 Final Thoughts & Closing: We wrap up with reflections, takeaways, and an open floor for last thoughts.

​This is not a lecture—it’s a conversation. Bring your point of view, your questions, and your curiosity. Get weird, get controversial, get real, baby. 

​Come for the ideas, stay for the drinks, lovers, and friends. 🍷

​*If you'd like to dig deeper on these texts, it is absolutely not required and you won't feel lost if you haven't. But we've put them together for you here, anyways.

​**idk what the rules of the Internet are these days please don't clown us for censoring

​***Seating is limited, so first come first serve. But standing is good for you, someone said somewhere once.

​****If cost is an issue, please reach out @cabbagehousekids, everyone is welcome!

events.name:
Modern
Kintsugi NY
events.description: The art of Kintsugi embodies new beauty made through imperfections. It’s an artistry of mending broken pieces, symbolically representing how brokenness in our lives can transform to places of beauty and power. Instead of hiding chipped and broken parts,when imperfections are pronounced with the gold, symbolizing the light, you behold something that’s more beautiful. It’s an art form of mending to make new. In this Gather, we’ll have an open time to share personal discovery with each other as we apply Kintsugi to a piece we’ve each brought with us. We’ll share a time of personal reflection and beholding through working with our hands.

events.name:
Suminagashi
Paper Marbling
events.description: Making marbled paper using ink, water, breath, and paper can connect us to the nature of life, art, and creative practice. In this Gather experience, explore the nature of Suminagashi, the meditative paper marbling process. You’ll learn the history of the process, learn how this marbling style connects to nature and play, be guided through the materials and steps, and meditate on the shape and form of ink as you make marbled paper design. Discover the mesmerizing, mindful creative practice of Suminagashi and relax into the flow.

events.name:
Tea
Formulation
events.description: There are many kinds of herbalism. But there’s greater healing potency when there’s thoughtfulness and care that goes into making unique blends for yourself and for others. This is caring for your health in a slower but more natural way. In this Gather, we’ll experience the intimacy of herbs through herbal tea formulation. We’ll explore the importance and beauty of knowing the whole constitution of a person, plant, and conditions. We’ll smell each herb and come to understand the broad strokes of the world of herbs. We’ll learn to thoughtfully compose custom blends for a uniquely designed human.

events.name: Ikebana
events.description: Flowers bring the beauty of the natural world inside. And Ikebana—the traditional Japanese art of flower arranging—allows us to play with movement, texture, and shape in order to create botanical sculptures. In this Gather, we’ll use farm fresh flowers, dried foliage, minimal ingredients, and simple mechanics to create two Ikebana designs. One design will be in a provided Ikebana vessel, and the other will be done in a vessel we’ve each brought with us. We’ll learn to attach flower frogs and explore different design approaches. We’ll then celebrate each others’ art pieces while enjoying light snacks and conversation.

events.name:
Playful
Mark Making
events.description: When a wash of ink spreads across the paper in an unanticipated way, we can become the creator of an exquisitely made mark. This kind of encounter can often happen when we approach a sketchbook with an attitude of play—with a new tool or a new way of moving the hand across the surface of the paper. In this Gather, we’ll explore how we make marks on a surface—like stamping with ink, drawing with a comb, and painting on yupo paper. We will experiment with these tools to create our own unique and unexpected textures. This can open up a new vocabulary of textures to apply to our creative practices across any medium.

events.name:
Architectural
Walk
events.description: HARLEM EDITION: Come cultivate the art of the city walk. Most New Yorkers pass places all the time without any knowledge of their context: either historical or modern. The walks will be designed for New Yorkers to see New York through the eyes of an architect: seeking to understand the big picture while appreciating the details. In this curated route, we will focus on the historic architecture of Harlem. As a neighborhood, Harlem is part physical, part mythical. The famed renaissance that transpired a hundred years ago has indelibly shaped the neighborhood’s identity as a Mecca culture and placemaking in New York City. We will be cultivating the art of city walking, not as tourists, but as architecture-aficionados, learning to appreciate the details of Harlem’s most distinct buildings and brownstones.

events.name:
Art
Collecting
events.description: We all encounter art throughout our lives, but becoming a patron of the arts can be intimidating. Where do we even begin? And why should we? In this Gather, we’ll learn about the world of art and art collecting—in an approachable way. What are galleries and how do they work? How can we develop our own relationship with art and artists? How can we start to budget, collect, and understand art as an investment? What is the ecosystem of the art world (including the artist, the gallery, the collector, the advisor, and the auction house), and how do we relate to it? We’ll end our time together with an exhibition tour of a ‘37x21x21’ a project exchange with artists from Vienna and New York.

events.name:
Art to
Exhibition
events.description: Both young and experienced creatives alike are often overwhelmed when navigating the nuances of the fine art scene. The art world can leave people hurt and directionless. But art galleries often look for a specific approach and a punch list of deliverables, even more than they look for the quality of work. In this Gather, we’ll discuss practical ways for conquering creative chaos, developing professionalism, starting and maintaining relationships with galleries, and presenting yourself and your work for potential exhibitions. We’ll give insider info on how galleries think and real talk about art pricing. We’ll explore how you can prepare a foundation for presenting yourself and your work to the world.

events.name:
Avatar
Painting
events.description: We all long to be seen and recognized. And there’s always an occasion to celebrate the people (and pets) in your life. In this Gather, we’ll create a lil’ piece of art that represents you or someone you love. We’ll look at how you can capture a person’s essence—just with a hairline and well-plotted eyes. We’ll ask what beauty you see in this person that you want to bring forth. And then we’ll sketch, paint, and podge a personalized wooden figure. After all, who wood-n’t want a selfie?

events.name:
Meditational
Calligraphy
events.description: Writing a letter by hand can create a deeper connection to the text, to the reader, and to oneself. In this Gather, we will cover the basic letter and the art of calligraphy. We will explore our own unique handwriting, finding the art within our personal marks. We will get comfortable using the calligraphy pen, and with can pens. We’ll explore how it can become a part of mindful practices and expressions.

events.name:
Contemplative
Bookbinding
events.description: Books are objects made for both intimate and collective spaces, to both be shared and to be enjoyed in solitude. They are vessels for our hearts, our stories, our voices. They store our memories, histories, and ideas. And so, how they are made is an important creative interplay with who we are and how we share and care for our thoughts. In this Gather, we’ll craft our own handmade notebooks through the Pamphlet Stitch Bookbinding process. With simple materials like cardstock, needle, and thread, we’ll use historical techniques and the presence of our current minds and bodies to create a space for our thoughts and dreams to roam.

events.name:
Wreath
Design
events.description: 12/13/2024 Holiday Edition: This December join Gather at the Manette Flower Co. Studio for an evening of festive fun and holiday wreath-making! We will play with a variety of textures, wintry foliage, ribbon, pinecones, and more. Light snacks and hot drinks will be provided. Each Gather participant will leave with a beautiful wreath to grace their front door.

events.name:
Floral
Design
events.description: In many cultures the exchange of flowers is a form of communication and an expression of our bond to each other and to nature. But floral symbolism is also very personal. In this Gather, we’ll explore our relationship to flowers, learning the feelings of different colors, textures, and forms of floral composition. We’ll spend time free-drawing with our whole bodies to get comfortable with natural flow. We’ll shake and tap the flowers to get a sense of how each flower moves, listening to their organic nature and to how they want to be. We’ll learn to construct our own bouquets connected to specific themes, occasions, or emotions that we want to express.

events.name:
Acting Tools for
Everyday
events.description: When acting, one must get out of the way for something new to arise. An actor strips away pretense and puts the self aside to honor the character and scene. This expression is why we watch actors. But the tools of acting can be used broadly in order to communicate more effectively. In this Gather, we’ll explore techniques that unlock the spoken and written word. We’ll discover the power of our own voices. We’ll practice the public interpretation of a text we’ve each brought with us, strengthening our intuition with them. We’ll explore tone, beats, and emotional nuances—and we’ll grow in awareness of how we communicate in daily life.

events.name:
Interpretative
Dreams
events.description: However dreams come to us—whether it’s divine communication or merely neurons firing for subconscious thought—there are moments in time when dreams are irrefutably important. In this Gather, we’ll explore the art of dream interpretation. We’ll process through writing and visuals, paying attention to the words, symbols, and prominent emotions of a specific dream. We’ll get comfortable engaging with our dreams, entering a multi-layered conversation with them to record and understand what they may be communicating.

events.name:
Modern
Kintsugi, MD
events.description: The art of Kintsugi embodies new beauty made through imperfections. It’s an artistry of mending broken pieces, symbolically representing how brokenness in our lives can transform to places of beauty and power. Instead of hiding chipped and broken parts, when imperfections are pronounced with the gold, symbolizing the light, you behold something that’s more beautiful. It’s an art form of mending to make new. In this Gather, we’ll have an open time to share personal discovery with each other as we apply Kintsugi to a piece we’ve each brought with us. We’ll share a time of personal reflection and beholding through working with our hands.

events.name:
Expressive
Poetics
events.description: In a poem, we don’t need to have the answers or know all the pieces of a story. In fact, a poem can help us say things we didn’t have words for, can help us uncover things we didn’t know or acknowledge within ourselves. For this Gather, we’ll explore the world within. Through a guided writing time, we’ll explore seven different movements of the mind—different mental approaches to the same item or event. This gets us out of our usual patterns of thinking and remembering, and also gets us out of the anxiety of “what am I going to write?” We’ll then craft a poem from the phrases we’ve unearthed. We’ll learn how to approach writing in a less direct and less pressured manner, and how to find the poetry that’s already there—in our own voices, in our own minds.

events.name:
Power
of Scent
events.description: We’re constantly surrounded by smell. A scent can instantly transport us elsewhere—to another place, another time, a strong emotion, a memory. And yet, scent is rarely celebrated in the sensory world. In this Gather, we’ll examine the science of scents, of how they’re constructed and layered. We’ll learn how to test scents to find one that jives with our body chemistry. We’ll explore how to use scent as a tool for self-expression, mood, and wardrobing, as we consider how we present ourselves through scent.

events.name:
Unearthing
Your Book
events.description: Writing a book starts with a single idea. But clarifying writing goals and navigating the road to publishing can be an overwhelming, confusing, and often discouraging process. In this Gather, we’ll demystify the publishing process and answer some key questions about publishing houses, about the difference between self-publishing and traditional publishing, and about how to take the next step toward putting words into the world. Perhaps your idea for a book is freshly thought, or perhaps it’s fully baked. Or perhaps you’re simply curious about what it might take to publish a book. We’ll spend time asking clarifying questions about our individual book ideas, and we’ll each walk away with the bones of a book proposal.

events.name:
Joyful
Water + Color
events.description: Water is something every child loves playing with. And when we paint with watercolor, we slow down—we layer water and colors to reveal what’s going on around us, outside of us, or even inside of us. In this Gather, we’re going to play with water and we’re going to add a little bit of color, giving and taking to see what can be revealed. We’ll learn about materials, color itself, and techniques such as wet-on-dry, wet-on-wet, layering, and feathering. We’ll see how time itself is an important tool in this process. And we’ll practice how to create a full scene, layering water and color to create dimension and depth.

events.name: Dispatches from the Field: Kim Frank
events.description:
Dispatches from the Field, a new digital program designed to bring The Explorers Club community closer—wherever you are. 
Each session kicks off with a 10-minute talk from a Featured Speaker, streamed live to the public on explorers.org and our YouTube channel. 
This will be followed by Campfire sessions—intimate, Members-Only breakout groups where you can connect, share ideas, and build relationships. 
  
This edition features Kim Frank FN’18, to present Into the Unknown: The Art of Expedition Storytelling: 
Exploration is about venturing into unknown and sharing what you’ve learned. The most compelling stories from the field bring together diverse cultures, scientific discoveries, and and personal journeys, resonating with a broader audience. Drawing from my experiences documenting the human-elephant conflict in India, I’ll share how expedition storytelling can inspire action and deepen our connection with each other and the natural world. 
Members only – click here to register.

events.name: Eyewitness to War
events.description:
Eyewitness to War: A Reporter’s Quest for Truth Amid a Landscape of Death and Deception
  
Join Explorers Club fellow and award-winning journalist Scott Wallace for a startling look into the armed conflicts that rocked Central America in the 1980s. 
  
This richly illustrated multimedia lecture will take the audience on an unforgettable journey into the jungles and bullet-scarred villages of Central America during the upheaval of the 1980s. Danger lurks at every turn as Scott Wallace ventures up rebel-infested mountain roads, boards helicopters buzzing the treetops to dodge heat-seeking missiles, and travels by dugout canoe along hotly contested waterways in his quest to uncover the truth. Based on his new visual and written memoir, Central America in the Crosshairs of War, the lecture will also raise timely questions about U.S. foreign policy, the uses of American military power, and the origins of the current immigration crisis on the southern border. This lecture will especially appeal to those interested in the intersection of exploration and war reportage, human and Indigenous rights, war photography, and the business of reporting the news in a time of widespread deception and disinformation. 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A. Scott will also have copies of his book available for signing. 

Streaming live here on explorers.org, our YouTube Channel, and our Facebook Live — Monday, February 24th at 7:00 pm ET. 
RESERVATIONS
This will be an in-person lecture at Explorers Club Headquarters. 
In-person tickets are $20 for Members, and $35 for the General Public. 
Check-in will begin at 6:00 pm, with a beer and wine reception from 6:00 – 7:00 pm

events.name: Invisible Iceberg: When Climate and Weather Shaped History
events.description:
Join The Explorers Club on Monday, March 3rd to learn about the wild, unexpected, and fascinating ways that weather has influenced and altered the outcomes of momentous events throughout history. 
AccuWeather Founder and Executive Chairman Dr. Joel N. Myers takes readers on a journey from the beginning of time to modern days, exploring how weather and climate impacted historic events around the globe in his book Invisible Iceberg: When Climate and Weather Shaped History. 
From the comet that ended the age of the dinosaur 66 million years ago, to engrossing stories about how weather and climate led to the rise and fall of empires, caused plagues to spread, inspired works of art, and thoughts on whether the movements of a cold front and a nearby hurricane could have thwarted the 9/11 attacks, the book highlights dozens of fascinating events from history, along with thought-provoking insight about how weather and climate are stitched into the outcomes of these historic occurrences. 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A. 

Streaming live here on explorers.org, our YouTube Channel, and our Facebook Live — Monday, March 3rd at 7:00 pm ET. 
RESERVATIONS
This will be an in-person lecture at Explorers Club Headquarters. 
In-person tickets are $20 for Members, and $35 for the General Public. 
Check-in will begin at 6:00 pm, with a beer and wine reception from 6:00 – 7:00 pm

events.name: ALTER EGO: Cloning, the Age of Reason?
events.description:
Join The Explorers Club for an in person screening of Alter Ego – The Age of Reason, a deep dive into the growing field of cloning. 
In his latest film, Alter Ego – The Age of Reason, Luc Hardy, French-American explorer-producer and environmental advocate, immerses us into the world of cloning, full of questions and promises… 
From Professor Ludovic Orlando’s research in the steppes of the Russian Altai to camel beauty contests in the United Arab Emirates, between ethics and scientific progress, this journey documents the divergent visions of cloning as well as its possible benefits for our ecosystems and mankind. 
 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A. 

A screening at the Explorers Club – Wednesday, March 10th at 7:00 pm ET.

This will be an in-person lecture at Explorers Club Headquarters.

events.name: Saturday Science for Students

events.name: Anne Morrow Lindbergh: Visionary Aviator and Explorer
events.description:
Join the Explorers Club and the Breaking Barriers committee on March 10th to celebrate the life of pioneering author and explorer Anne Morrow Lindbergh. 
  
On May 27th, 1929, Anne Spencer Morrow, a quite shy, prize-winning English major and graduate of Smith College, married Charles A. Lindbergh, the most famous aviator of his time and the world’s first media star. Not surprisingly this changed her life radically. In five years, by 1934, she would be referred to in the media as the “First Lady of Aviation” on her own merits. This amazing transformation would not only include her learning to fly, getting her radio license, and becoming a fully licensed glider pilot, but also opened the door to many very real flying accomplishments and adventures as she accompanied her husband as navigator, radio operator, and co-pilot, exploring the uses of aviation, then a new technology, in exploration, science, communication, and relief work. 
Anne’s contributions to exploration include: 

Acting as co-pilot and navigator with her husband to set a transcontinental record.
Spotting from the air an important and previously undiscovered Mayan temple.
Photo-documenting areas of the Canyon de Chelly that are still extremely difficult to reach.
Identifying a previously unknown mountain range in Greenland.
Flying 40,000 miles with her husband acting as co-pilot, radio operator, and navigator, surveying national and international air routes, many still in use today.
Making a record breaking radio transmission of 3,000 miles, establishing a new long distance record.

Her two books on her flying experiences during the Golden Age of Flight were best sellers and won the National Bookseller Association National Book Awards for non-fiction. Her first book, NORTH TO THE ORIENT, marking it’s 90th year in print in 2025, won the first National Book Award for non-fiction in 1935. 
  
 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A. 

Streaming live here on explorers.org, our YouTube Channel, and our Facebook Live — Monday, March 10th at 7:00 pm ET.

events.name: Nanuk Narratives
events.description:
Nanuk Narratives: Voices of the People Living Alongside Polar Bears
  
“Nanuk Narratives” is an Inuit-led series of short documentary films about the deep and enduring relationship among Inuit and polar bears (nanuk). Hearing directly from Inuit across the Canadian Arctic and Greenland, these videos explore a diversity of topics, including Inuit observations of bear abundance and health, human-bear encounters and safety, tracking and hunting bears, cooking and eating bears, the cultural and emotional connections to bears, and Inuit recommendations for polar bear management. 
This event will be presented by David Borish, the director of this initiative, who is also an EC50 Class of 2023 member. David will screen a variety of short films that hear from community voices, and talk about the process of co-creating films in partnership with Inuit communities, wildlife co-management boards, local filmmakers, researchers, and others. David will also share his experience filming polar bears across the Arctic, including skidooing in temperatures below -40 fahrenheit, and the sailing through the Northwest Passage on Le Commandant Charcot icebreaker. 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A.

events.name: Blown Away - Searching for the Legendary Khamsin Winds
events.description:
Sometimes, one moment on an expedition can be so impactful it changes the way we think about the world around us, even for a veteran explorer familiar with the area. This is what happened to Tom Paradise and his team when the fierce Khamsin desert winds enveloped his expedition party in Wadi Rum last year. Join Tom and The Explorers Club for a personal account and investigation into this powerful phenomenon.  
Having worked in southern Jordan since 1990, Tom Paradise has slept in Bedouin tents, studied the desert, climbed Mount Nebo and Jebel Haroun – the legendary burial sites of Moses and his brother Aaron, and has documented hundreds of Nabatean tombs and monuments. However, the rare, and often ferocious Khamsin winds have constantly eluded Paradise and his teams. However, in May 2024, when on an Explorers Club Flag Expedition in Wadi Rum near the Saudi border, he and his group were fortuitously loaded with field equipment when the extraordinary winds hit. Lasting only 83 minutes, the southerly winds stirred up the desert floor creating a solid wall of dust and sand.  The gales gusted up to 100 kph (65mph) while the team recorded the dramatic event. Not only was it an outrageous experience, these ‘winds of legend‘ profoundly challenged our understanding about desert landforms and environmental dynamics. Was such a rare and savage episode able to change the desert cliffs and dune fields blowing only a few hours each year, or was it our current conventional theories of everyday processes (uniformitarianism) that truly change the landscape around us?  For a team of veteran field geoscientists and grad students, our way of looking at desert landforms was changed forever… 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A. 

Streaming live here on explorers.org, our YouTube Channel, and our Facebook Live — Monday, March 17th at 7:00 pm ET.

events.name: Navigating Drought: Predators, People, and Coexistence
events.description:
When faced with drought, how do Africa’s great predators adjust their behavior to survive? Join Leigh West, a wildlife researcher and Explorers Club grantee, as she shares how lions, leopards, cheetahs, and African wild dogs change their movements when water sources dwindle and prey becomes scarce. Discover how these predators interact with one another and share the landscape with people as they adapt to increasingly frequent and severe environmental challenges. 
Through captivating stories from her fieldwork in Botswana’s Okavango Delta, Leigh will reveal how understanding predator behavior during extreme climate events can help foster coexistence between people and wildlife. Using 13 years of GPS data from these carnivores encompassing several droughts, Leigh’s research highlights how drought can reshape carnivore behavior, from shifting movement patterns to changing exposure to humans, and has direct implications for conservation in a changing climate. 
Perfect for adventurers, conservationists, and anyone fascinated by the resilience of wildlife and the challenges of living alongside them! 
 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A. 

Streaming live here on explorers.org, our YouTube Channel, and our Facebook Live — Monday, March 24th at 7:00 pm ET.

events.name: Saving India's Wildlife
events.description:
Join the Explorers Club and Wildlife SOS for a look into past and ongoing efforts to preserve India’s threatened wildlife. 
Wildlife SOS is widely recognized for one of India’s most remarkable conservation successes—the eradication of the cruel practice of dancing bears. Building on this achievement, the organization is applying its expertise to tackle other pressing wildlife conservation challenges in India, including the protection of Asian elephants. 
Asian elephants are an endangered species, with fewer than 40,000 individuals remaining worldwide. Over 60% of this population is found in India, making the country critical to the species’ long-term survival. Indian elephant populations face significant threats, including habitat fragmentation, human-wildlife conflict, and the ongoing demand for elephants in captivity. Wildlife SOS is working to both improve the welfare of captive elephants as well as implementing creative strategies to protect them in the wild. 
Kartick Satyanarayan, Wildlife SOS co-founder, and one of the world’s most notable wildlife warriors, will be telling stories from his experiences in the field to conserve and protect India’s wildlife. 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A.

events.name: Summiting Everest Without Oxygen
events.description:
Join the Explorers Club and famed alpinist Melissa Arnot Reid for a first hand account of her journey to become the first American woman to summit Everest without supplemental oxygen. 
In May of 2016 Melissa Arnot Reid became the first American woman to summit Mount Everest without the use of supplemental oxygen. It was her sixth summit of the peak and the culmination of nine seasons of working as a mountain guide on Everest and around the world. The journey to arriving at the summit, and surviving the descent, was one filled with physical and emotional challenges that required her to dive deep into her own motivation for being there and face the truth of the life and death stakes of trying something nearly impossible. To celebrate the release of her memoir, ENOUGH: CLIMBING TOWARD A TRUE SELF ON MOUNT EVEREST, Melissa will share the story behind her motivation, the road to being ready, and the details of her historic climb–most of which have never been shared publicly. A story of personal reflection, growth, and healing on the highest peak on earth containing lessons learned in the mountains, but of use to everyone regardless of what your own mountain is in life. 
  
 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A. Books will be available for purchase. 

Streaming live here on explorers.org, our YouTube Channel, and our Facebook Live — Monday, March 31st at 7:00 pm ET.

events.name: AFTER THE NORTH POLE: A Story of Survival, Mythmaking, and Melting Ice
events.description:
Join legendary explorer Erling Kagge for a deep dive into the stories, both personal and historical, of polar exploration. Kagge will take attendees through his own adventures in the polar regions and beyond, as well as share  reflections on the nature of exploration at large. 
Erling Kagge takes us on a journey through the history of wild imaginings, broken hearts, and life dreams achieved at 70 degrees below zero. Kagge was the first in history to reach the North Pole, South Pole and summit of Everest on foot, and he reveals what he learned in the shifting ice about what drives the polar explorer, from the earliest historical records to now. 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A.

events.name: Further Explorations of the Titanic
events.description:
On the evening of April 14—113 years after the Titanic struck the iceberg that sealed its fate—this presentation explores three areas of study worth continuing on the legendary vessel.  
First, we’ll examine how the Titanic serves as a living laboratory for marine biologists and oceanographers. The wreck has become an unprecedented case study of deep-sea decomposition, offering insights into how metal structures deteriorate in extreme conditions and supporting unique ecosystems of “rusticles” and specialized microorganisms. 
The second segment addresses the ongoing ethical debate surrounding salvage operations. We’ll analyze the tension between preserving historical artifacts and maintaining the site’s integrity as a maritime grave, examining recent court decisions and competing claims from salvage companies and preservation groups. 
Finally, we’ll delve into the often-overlooked ethnic diversity among Titanic’s passengers. While popular media typically focuses on wealthy first-class travelers from the United States and United Kingdom, the ship carried a rich tapestry of immigrants from across Europe, the Middle East, and Asia. We’ll explore the stories of passengers from places like Lebanon, Croatia, and even China, examining their reasons for travel and how their experiences reflect broader patterns of early 20th-century migration. 
Together, these perspectives offer fresh insights into one of history’s most studied maritime disasters, demonstrating that science will carry Titanic’s legacy forward as much as legend. 
  
Schwankert’s new book The Six will be available for purchase and signing after the presentation. 
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A. 

Streaming live here on explorers.org, our YouTube Channel, and our Facebook Live — Monday, April 14th at 7:00 pm ET.

events.name: Derek Parfit's Birthday!
events.description:
Derek Parfit was perhaps the greatest moral philosopher of the 20th century, in how he shaped the discipline and raised important new questions. 

He gave us the Repugnant Conclusion and the Hitchhiker's Dilemma, and put a plug for giving 10% into On What Matters, his masterpiece. Had he lived long enough to finish another volume, he had plans to discuss existential risk and dive deeper into questions of how we ought to act.

How to celebrate Parfit's life and work? You could discuss population ethics, philosophize about something else, or consider, as a group, ways to make your lives slightly more rational. (Or just eat cake and sing Happy Birthday and engage in idle, friendly conversation; Parfit surely wouldn't object.)

TNS usually skates about 18-20 miles (30 km) and travels to locations in upper Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx, or over the GWB to New Jersey. Depending on the route, skaters may hang out afterwards to have a drink and hear some music at a pub or just get a slice of pizza.

This is a high-intermediate to advanced group skate. Skaters must be accustomed to skating after dark and on city streets with traffic. The pace is a bit faster and the distance a bit longer than most group skates.

Safety: Please wear helmet and wrist guards. Light-colored or reflective clothing is also recommended as are blinkies or other illumination.

More info on the Empire TNS webpage.

Leaders: Jimmy & Eric
Difficulty: High-intermediate to advanced

TNS starts meeting up 8:00 p.m. at the General Sherman monument at the corner of Fifth Ave and 60th St. and rolls out soon after. This is also the southeast entrance to Central Park.

TNS usually skates about 18-20 miles (30 km) and travels to locations in upper Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx, or over the GWB to New Jersey. Depending on the route, skaters may hang out afterwards to have a drink and hear some music at a pub or just get a slice of pizza.

This is a high-intermediate to advanced group skate. Skaters must be accustomed to skating after dark and on city streets with traffic. The pace is a bit faster and the distance a bit longer than most group skates.

Safety: Please wear helmet and wrist guards. Light-colored or reflective clothing is also recommended as are blinkies or other illumination.

More info on the Empire TNS webpage.

Leaders: Jimmy & Eric
Difficulty: High-intermediate to advanced

events.name: Empire-Brooklyn Speed Training
events.description:
Group inline speedskating practice on the Prospect Park loop organized by the Empire and Brooklyn Speed Teams.

Practices are held Sunday mornings from the start of April until the end of September, but may begin in March and end in October if weather and temperatures permit.

Meet-up is at the Bartel-Pritchard Circle entrance to Prospect Park, at the intersection of Prospect Park West and 15th St. Start time varies from 8:30 or 9 a.m. most of the summer but may be later in spring and autumn, depending on expected general use of the loop. So always check in with the Empire Speed FB page and/or with other skaters beforehand to find out exactly when it is.

The first loop is usually a warm up loop, and new-ish speedskaters should be able to hang on. After that the pace speeds up, and slower skaters may have to form a B group.

events.name: NYC Wednesday Night Skate
events.description:
NYC's largest group skate, rolling spring through autumn.

WNS starts meeting about 7:45 p.m. on the south side of Union Square, at the intersection of Broadway and 14th S., and rolls out at 8:00.

WNS skates about 12-15 miles (20-25 km). Most routes are circuits around Manhattan, perhaps looping around Midtown and Downtown or maybe heading up to Grant's Tomb and back. But WNS sometimes crosses the bridges to Queens and/or Brooklyn, such as during its popular Three Bridges skate.

WNS usually finishes about 10:15, ending at a skate friendly pub near Union Square.

WNS is an intermediate level group skate. Skaters must be accustomed to skating after dark and on city streets with traffic. The pace is typical of most group skates.

Safety: Please wear helmet and wrist guards. Light-colored or reflective clothing is also recommended as are blinkies or other illumination.

More info and announcements available on the WNS Facebook page.

Leader: WNS Staff
Level: Intermediate to advanced.

New York City's oldest group skate, rolling the streets of the city since 1989. Sponsored by the Empire Skate Club since 1997.

TNS starts meeting up 8:00 p.m. at the General Sherman monument at the corner of Fifth Ave and 60th St. and rolls out soon after. This is also the southeast entrance to Central Park.

TNS usually skates about 18-20 miles (30 km) and travels to locations in upper Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx, or over the GWB to New Jersey. Depending on the route, skaters may hang out afterwards to have a drink and hear some music at a pub or just get a slice of pizza.

This is a high-intermediate to advanced group skate. Skaters must be accustomed to skating after dark and on city streets with traffic. The pace is a bit faster and the distance a bit longer than most group skates.

Safety: Please wear helmet and wrist guards. Light-colored or reflective clothing is also recommended as are blinkies or other illumination.

More info on the Empire TNS webpage.

Leaders: Jimmy & Eric
Difficulty: High-intermediate to advanced

venue.address: General William Tecumseh Sherman Monument, 764 Doris C Freedman Pl, New York, NY 10019, USA

events.name: NYC Wednesday Night Skate
events.description:
NYC's largest group skate, rolling spring through autumn.

WNS starts meeting about 7:45 p.m. on the south side of Union Square, at the intersection of Broadway and 14th S., and rolls out at 8:00.

WNS skates about 12-15 miles (20-25 km). Most routes are circuits around Manhattan, perhaps looping around Midtown and Downtown or maybe heading up to Grant's Tomb and back. But WNS sometimes crosses the bridges to Queens and/or Brooklyn, such as during its popular Three Bridges skate.

WNS usually finishes about 10:15, ending at a skate friendly pub near Union Square.

WNS is an intermediate level group skate. Skaters must be accustomed to skating after dark and on city streets with traffic. The pace is typical of most group skates.

Safety: Please wear helmet and wrist guards. Light-colored or reflective clothing is also recommended as are blinkies or other illumination.

More info and announcements available on the WNS Facebook page.

Leader: WNS Staff
Level: Intermediate to advanced.

venue.address: Union Square, New York, NY 10003, USA

events.name: Empire Speed CP Loop Training
events.description:
Group inline speedskating practice on the Central Park loop by the Empire Skate Club's speed team.

Meet-up is at Speedskaters Curb, located on the west side of the Central Park loop just north of Tavern on the Green (W 67th St.), at 7 p.m.

Empire Speed training in Central Park from mid spring to mid autumn usually occurs one or two weekday evenings per week. Please note that this Thursday session is weather permitting. There is no make-up date in case of rain.

Announcements and updates about Empire Speed sessions are posted on the Empire Speed Facebook page, often with short notice (rarely more than 24 hours, and often just maybe 9-10 hours).

venue.address: Warner LeRoy Place, Warner LeRoy Pl, New York, NY, USA

events.name: Empire-Brooklyn Speed Training
events.description:
Group inline speedskating practice on the Prospect Park loop organized by the Empire and Brooklyn Speed Teams.

Practices are held Sunday mornings from the start of April until the end of September, but may begin in March and end in October if weather and temperatures permit.

Meet-up is at the Bartel-Pritchard Circle entrance to Prospect Park, at the intersection of Prospect Park West and 15th St. Start time varies from 8:30 or 9 a.m. most of the summer but may be later in spring and autumn, depending on expected general use of the loop. So always check in with the Empire Speed FB page and/or with other skaters beforehand to find out exactly when it is.

The first loop is usually a warm up loop, and new-ish speedskaters should be able to hang on. After that the pace speeds up, and slower skaters may have to form a B group.

events.name: We Skate NJ Night Skate
events.description:
Group skate long the NJ waterfront across the river from the city.

WSNJ rolls on Mondays, weather permitting. Meet up is at the Son Cubano restaurant in West New York, and roll-out is at 7:00 p.m.. Distance is about 12 miles, and mostly stays close to the waterfront in WNY and adjacent towns and is not hilly.

Safety: Please wear helmet and wrist guards. Light-colored or reflective clothing is also recommended as are blinkies or other illumination.

Further information might be available via the WSNJ Insta page.

venue.address: Son Cubano Restaurant on the Hudson, 40-4 Riverwalk Pl, West New York, NJ 07093, USA

events.name: Big Apple Roll (Tentative)
events.description:
This is a tentative calendar entry. Event dates will not be confirmed until spring 2025.

New York City's annual group skate weekend, organized by the Empire Skate Club.

The skating begins Wednesday evening with a special edition of the Wednesday Night Skate. There will then be Empire-organized group skates Thursday evening, Friday morning and evening, Saturday morning/afternoon and Sunday morning/afternoon.

The Friday evening skate should conclude with a party, and the turnaround for Saturday's long skate should be at a restaurant. There will also be raffles, clinics and more.

All Empire-organized group skates that are part of the Big Apple Roll will start from the event hotel.

Health and safety notice: Please wear helmet and wrist guards. Light-colored or reflective clothing is also recommended during evening/night skates, as are blinkies or other illumination. 

Many more details about BAR can be found on the event website.

Leader: Empire staff

venue.address: Marriott Downtown, 8 Albany St, New York, NY 10006, USA

events.name: Empire-Brooklyn Speed Training
events.description:
Group inline speedskating practice on the Prospect Park loop organized by the Empire and Brooklyn Speed Teams.

Practices are held Sunday mornings from the start of April until the end of September, but may begin in March and end in October if weather and temperatures permit.

Meet-up is at the Bartel-Pritchard Circle entrance to Prospect Park, at the intersection of Prospect Park West and 15th St. Start time varies from 8:30 or 9 a.m. most of the summer but may be later in spring and autumn, depending on expected general use of the loop. So always check in with the Empire Speed FB page and/or with other skaters beforehand to find out exactly when it is.

The first loop is usually a warm up loop, and new-ish speedskaters should be able to hang on. After that the pace speeds up, and slower skaters may have to form a B group.

Empire Speed training in Central Park from mid spring to mid autumn usually occurs one or two weekday evenings per week. Please note that this Thursday session is weather permitting. There is no make-up date in case of rain.

venue.address: Warner LeRoy Place, Warner LeRoy Pl, New York, NY, USA

events.name: Northshore Inline Marathon
events.description:
USA's biggest inline racing event, a point-to-point along Lake Superior finishing in Duluth. Shorter options also available.

Event festivities start on Friday with an expo.

See the event website for more info.

events.name: Empire-Brooklyn Speed Training
events.description:
Group inline speedskating practice on the Prospect Park loop organized by the Empire and Brooklyn Speed Teams.

Practices are held Sunday mornings from the start of April until the end of September, but may begin in March and end in October if weather and temperatures permit.

Meet-up is at the Bartel-Pritchard Circle entrance to Prospect Park, at the intersection of Prospect Park West and 15th St. Start time varies from 8:30 or 9 a.m. most of the summer but may be later in spring and autumn, depending on expected general use of the loop. So always check in with the Empire Speed FB page and/or with other skaters beforehand to find out exactly when it is.

The first loop is usually a warm up loop, and new-ish speedskaters should be able to hang on. After that the pace speeds up, and slower skaters may have to form a B group.

Safety: Please wear helmet and wrist guards. Light-colored or reflective clothing is also recommended as are blinkies or other illumination.

Further information might be available via the WSNJ Insta page.

events.name: Pre-Marathon Speed Skate
events.description:
Informal (as in, not sponsored by any organization) group skate following the course of the NYC Marathon before the runners take over. This is a fast paced skate for advanced skaters. Group will start rolling ASAP and will endeavor to follow as much of the course as possible before the Queensboro Bridge is blocked off and before the streets are closed off by the police. If skaters make good time, they can roll over the QBB traffic lanes without (OMG, the embarrassment) taking the subway across the East River.

Safety/health notice: Helmet and other protective gear are strongly recommended.

Level: Advanced

events.name: Empire Sunday Marathon Watching Skate
events.description:
Group skate to watch runners in the NYC Marathon.

Group meets at Dante Park at Broadway and West 63rd St (across from Lincoln Center) at 9:30 a.m. and skates to East Harlem to see the lead runners heading up First Ave. and again as they head down Fifth Ave. Afterwards, the group will roll around upper Manhattan and the Bronx to watch and cheer on later runners. The group might also make a visit to the Bronx Brewery and/or Yankee Stadium and/or the High Bridge and/or a skate-friendly restaurant.

This group skate will include skating on city streets. Skaters must be accustomed to skating alongside city traffic.

Safety/health notice: Helmet and protection gear are strongly recommended.

Leader: Westchester Pete
Level: Intermediate

venue.address: Dante Park, Columbus Ave &, W 63rd St., New York, NY 10023, USA

TNS usually skates about 18-20 miles (30 km) and travels to locations in upper Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx, or over the GWB to New Jersey. Depending on the route, skaters may hang out afterwards to have a drink and hear some music at a pub or just get a slice of pizza.

This is a high-intermediate to advanced group skate. Skaters must be accustomed to skating after dark and on city streets with traffic. The pace is a bit faster and the distance a bit longer than most group skates.

Safety: Please wear helmet and wrist guards. Light-colored or reflective clothing is also recommended as are blinkies or other illumination.

More info on the Empire TNS webpage.

events.name: Audio Working Group – February meeting
events.description: We’ll discuss episodes we’re working on for the Audio Interference podcast, amongst other things. All are welcome. It’s in person and hybrid. for oom details reach out via basecamp or send an email to audio at interferencearchive dot org.

events.name: Education Reading Group
events.description:
The Education Reading Group is a place where we plan to share and discuss readings about transformative teaching, political pedagogy, engaging education, and the like.


For our next gathering, we will be reading the 
“The University and the Undercommons” chapter from Fred Moten and Stefano Harney’s 
The Undercommons: Fugitive Planning & Black Study
.


The meeting will take place online. You can find 
a link to meet here
.

events.name: A Skill-Share Workshop Series: Patches
events.description:
Come to the Education Working Group’s first installment of their Skill-Share Workshop series. We’ll be talking about patches! Volunteers will give a brief overview of patches as an aspect of punk and DIY culture, we’ll take a look together at some materials in the archive, and we’ll also host a participatory demonstration on how to make and sew your own patches.


This event will take place in person at the archive on Monday, February 10th at 6:30pm. We’ll have some limited supplies available on a first come, first serve basis, but bring something to sew your patch onto as well as any other supplies you might feel like using (tough fabric scraps, needle, thread, fabric markers).

events.name: Cultural workers for Palestine in NYC
events.description:
A community panel discussion and live broadcast on Radio AlHara, PalestineSaturday, Feb. 15, 5PM (doors) 6PM (panel)


Featuring :


Nadia Khayrallah
, Dancers for Palestine


Sam Sundos
, Palestinian-American interdisciplinary artist living and working in Brooklyn, NY


Yasmeen Abdallah
, Artist and co-founder of Fiber Friends of Falastin


Lianah, Theater Workers for a Ceasefire


Discussion hosted by Montreal based musician and community organizer 
Stefan Christoff
.


Organized in collaboration with Interference Archive.


This event brings together a panel of cultural workers from the New York City area who have been actively organizing and taking collective action to support Palestine over the last year. This community panel discussion at 
Interference Archive
 will stream live globally at 
radioalhara.net
 and also directly at 
The Wonder Cabinet
 in Bethlehem, Palestine. 


The goal of this event is to highlight the ways that cultural work is a key part of both broader community organizing practices and the contemporary movement to support Palestine. This discussion aims to highlight the ways that cultural work occurs as part of a process of exchange between artistic ideas but also organizational strategies that are built across grassroots organizing networks.


This panel builds on similar live community discussions with cultural workers that have recently taken place in other cities, also broadcast on Radio AlHara and hosted by Stefan Christoff, including in July 2024 at 
Casa do Comum
 in Lisbon, Portugal, in Amsterdam in Nov. at 
OT301
, in Mexico City in Feb. 2024 at Radio Nopal (
audio
) and in Sofia, Bulgaria at the 
коприва Feminist cultural space
. 


Information on the speakers and participating groups / collectives:


Drawing from the personal and the political through resilience and persistence, 
Yasmeen Abdallah
 references her Levantine lineage in the form of magic carpets, intimate weaving, and needle art practices. Abdallah seeks to create safe, mobile spaces in the face of occupying forces that cruelly and catastrophically fail humanity. She views the threaded needle as a tool of solidarity to rip through borders, unravel fictive allegories, and heal holes in tender hearts. Abdallah holds Bachelor’s degrees from University of Massachusetts in Anthropology (emphasis in Historical & Collaborative Archaeology, which included field schools with New England indigenous tribal communities); and another in Studio Art with honors, including a Minor in Women’s, Gender & Sexuality Studies. Abdallah also earned an MFA in Fine Arts with distinction from Pratt Institute. Her work as an artist, curator, writer, and educator is rooted in social engagement and collaborative work with various communities and DIY spaces including ABC No Rio; Art in Odd Places; Flux Factory; and Museum of Reclaimed Urban Space. She has been a visiting and teaching artist at institutions including New Museum; Pratt Institute; Sarah Lawrence; Residency Unlimited; BRIC; Kean University; Parsons; Children’s Museum of NYC; El Barrio Artspace; Fairleigh Dickinson; and University of Massachusetts. 


Dancers for Palestine
 (D4P) is an autonomous group of dance workers who organize in solidarity with the global movement for Palestinian liberation. Formed during Israel’s genocidal attack on Gaza beginning in 2023, D4P seeks to both cohere and create a dance community which is vocal and active in its support of the Palestinian people. D4P is a local and international endeavor with a core organizing group in NYC and an ever expanding network of dancers and organizers. D4P’s work has included protest and direct action, political education events, art-based fundraising, and campaigns to move dance institutions into alignment with the Palestinian Academic and Cultural Boycott of Israel.


Fiber Friends of Falastin
 is an exploratory social activity for folks who have basic crochet, knitting, sewing, quilting, weaving, embroidery, (and more!) skills. Taking place at Interference Archive, this is open to all who are interested in building community at the intersection of textile-making and social movements, where work is created in support of Palestine. 


Sam Sundos
 is a Palestinian-American interdisciplinary artist living and working in Brooklyn, NY. Through his paintings & textiles Sundos references his experience as a Palestinian born & raised in diaspora while applying the use of traditional slow craft processes and cultural iconography. Through incorporating his personal experience to these processes Sundos’ hopes to use his voice to advance conversations centering around imperialism & its socioeconomic effects while remaining grounded in themes of indigeneity & tradition. In short, through his art, Sundos seeks to convey the significance of human touch and the value of every human life. Sundos has also recently founded 
Unibrow Sun
, an organization prioritizing artists & activists whose work is focused on elevating narratives of solidarity through exhibitions, screening, workshops & printed material.


Theater Workers for a Ceasefire
 exists to organize U.S.-based theater workers in solidarity with the people of Palestine. We aim to use our bodies and talents in pursuit of a comprehensive ceasefire, which we understand is merely the first step among many in realizing a Free Palestine.

events.name: Volunteer Orientation
events.description:
Join us for the next volunteer orientation to learn about Interference Archive’s collection, how we work together as a nonhierarchical community archive, ways to get involved, and meet fellow comrades and volunteers.


This orientation is open to everyone
; established volunteers who want a refresher and to new folks trying to plug into the community. It doesn’t matter whether you’ve shadowed once, have put on 10 exhibitions, or have just been lurking on the newsletter—all are welcome to learn, share, and make things happen through the archive! We hope you leave this orientation with new friends, new contacts to help you do the work you’re passionate about, and a clearer sense of Interference’s history, communication channels, and values. Come with your questions and ideas!


Space is limited, 
so please RSVP
 to reserve your spot for this session!


Physical space of the Interference Archive is ADA compliant.


Due to current COVID rates, masking is currently required during events at Interference Archive. We will provide masks at the door.

events.name: Intro to Self-Defense Workshop
events.description:
Join us for a free intro self-defense workshop at Interference Archive!
We’ll be covering the basics: stretching, conditioning, technique, and theory, with the hope that participants will leave with some super useful foundations that they can add to their self-defense toolkits.
Mix that in with movement and pad-hitting and you’ll have an accessible and confidence-boosting good time for all. This workshop is great for beginners, meant to share some simple-to-pick-up techniques that you can practice on your own or with friends!


Space is limited, so 
please register your interest here
! 


Due to current COVID rates, masking is encouraged during events at Interference Archive.




/

events.name: Winter Village in Bryant Park
The Orchid Show
events.description: The Orchid Show: Mexican Modernism Promises a Breathtaking Display of Orchids in a Sensory Journey to Mexico City, from February 15 through  April 27, 2025.\nExperience the vibrant hues and captivating beauty of The Orchid Show: Mexican Modernism. Embark on a journey to Mexico City, where the fusion of tradition and modern artistry takes center stage amid breathtaking displays of orchids. Wander through lush landscapes adorned with thousands of orchids, showcasing Mexico’s diverse ecosystems and rich cultural history. Marvel at intricate arrangements of orchids in displays that evoke the color-saturated designs of Mexican modernist architect Luis Barragán transported to the nybg.org • T 718.817.8700 • F 718.220.6504 2900 Southern Boulevard, Bronx, NY 10458-5126Bronx. Whether you’re a seasoned orchid enthusiast or an NYBG newcomer, this exhibition promises a feast for the senses and a celebration of Mexico’s rich botanical history. On select Saturday evenings during The Orchid Show, adults 21 and over can experience Orchid Nights, a picture-perfect night out, with music and dancing, cash bars, and food available for purchase.  \n

events.description: The Orchid Show: Mexican Modernism Promises a Breathtaking Display of Orchids in a Sensory Journey to Mexico City, from February 15 through  April 27, 2025.\nExperience the vibrant hues and captivating beauty of The Orchid Show: Mexican Modernism. Embark on a journey to Mexico City, where the fusion of tradition and modern artistry takes center stage amid breathtaking displays of orchids. Wander through lush landscapes adorned with thousands of orchids, showcasing Mexico’s diverse ecosystems and rich cultural history. Marvel at intricate arrangements of orchids in displays that evoke the color-saturated designs of Mexican modernist architect Luis Barragán transported to the nybg.org • T 718.817.8700 • F 718.220.6504 2900 Southern Boulevard, Bronx, NY 10458-5126Bronx. Whether you’re a seasoned orchid enthusiast or an NYBG newcomer, this exhibition promises a feast for the senses and a celebration of Mexico’s rich botanical history. On select Saturday evenings during The Orchid Show, adults 21 and over can experience Orchid Nights, a picture-perfect night out, with music and dancing, cash bars, and food available for purchase.  \n

events.name: Easter Parade and Easter Bonnet Festival
events.description: Each year on Easter, celebrants don festive finery and show off their very best bonnets along Fifth Avenue. Immortalized by Irving Berlin (with some help from Judy Garland and Fred Astaire), the pageant is a New York City tradition that stretches back to the 1870s.Starting at about 10am and continuing until 4pm, the parade marches north on Fifth Avenue, from 49th Street to 57th Street. The best place to watch is from the area around St. Patrick's Cathedral; better yet, bring your bonnet and join the parade.

venue.name: The parade marches north on Fifth Avenue, from 49th Street to 57th Street.

events.name: Apply to the Compost & Farm Apprenticeship with Earth Matter NY
events.type: Apply to the Compost & Farm Apprenticeship with Earth Matter NY
events.description: The free Compost & Farm Apprenticeship with Earth Matter NY offers GreenThumb gardeners the opportunity to work with Earth Matter NY and learn hands-on practical skills to grow plants on a small scale urban farm, with a focus on composting. You will learn how to make “Gold Standard” compost in a variety of urban environments. You will be engaging with a variety of composting procedures, devices and systems with the goal of utilizing best practices for the improvement of soil and plant health.Learn more and apply: bit.ly/EarthMatterSpring25 Deadline: Monday, February 17, at 11:59 p.m.Dates: 10 full-day Friday sessions from March 14 - May 16, 2025Location: Soil Start Farm, located on Governors Island.Eligibility:This training is for members of registered GreenThumb gardens (ages 18+) who are interested in growing their composting and vegetable production skills to the next level, acquiring green job skills, and spreading knowledge of composting best practices in New York City. We encourage gardeners to apply with another member from their garden. Both members still need to submit applications separately.
category: Apply to the Compost & Farm Apprenticeship with Earth Matter NY
tags: Apply to the Compost & Farm Apprenticeship with Earth Matter NY

events.name: Arsenal Gallery: Brooklyn Dreamland, Land without Shadows
events.type: Arsenal Gallery: Brooklyn Dreamland, Land without Shadows
events.description: NYC Parks is pleased to present Brooklyn Dreamland, Land without Shadows, an exhibition of paintings and drawings by Christopher Spinelli depicting a bygone era of Coney Island on view at the Arsenal Gallery.In the late 1980s, Spinelli was encouraged by illustrator Robert Weaver to get out of the studio and explore real life. Childhood trips piled in his father's car in search of crinkle-cut fries led him to the B train, where he rode to the end of the line. Equipped with a sketch pad and Polaroid camera, Spinelli produced many drawings and images of the then-declining amusement site. Regarding these initial works, he states, "I began talking to the denizens of Coney Island, who were usually huddled in and around Nathan's for warmth; I drew them while they regaled me with their stories. Some of those first sketches are included in this exhibit." Inspired by buzzing neon signs and accumulated layers of peeling paint, Spinelli began producing the wonderfully garish acrylic works featured in this exhibition.Unlike his drawings, his paintings are rendered from childhood memory rather than present experience. He states, "My paintings of Coney Island are vibrantly colored and thickly textured; I am painting not as I found it, but what I remember seeing in those fleeting images from the back window of that Delta 88 as we drove by." This exhibition is FREE and open to the public. For more information, visit nyc.gov/parks/art. A public opening reception will be held on Thursday, January 23, 2025, at 6 p.m. Image Credit: Christopher Spinelli, This Way to the Spookarama, 2021, acrylic paint, 36”x48”
category: Arsenal Gallery: Brooklyn Dreamland, Land without Shadows
tags: Arsenal Gallery: Brooklyn Dreamland, Land without Shadows

events.name: Arsenal Gallery: Brooklyn Dreamland, Land without Shadows
events.type: Arsenal Gallery: Brooklyn Dreamland, Land without Shadows
events.description: NYC Parks is pleased to present Brooklyn Dreamland, Land without Shadows, an exhibition of paintings and drawings by Christopher Spinelli depicting a bygone era of Coney Island on view at the Arsenal Gallery.In the late 1980s, Spinelli was encouraged by illustrator Robert Weaver to get out of the studio and explore real life. Childhood trips piled in his father's car in search of crinkle-cut fries led him to the B train, where he rode to the end of the line. Equipped with a sketch pad and Polaroid camera, Spinelli produced many drawings and images of the then-declining amusement site. Regarding these initial works, he states, "I began talking to the denizens of Coney Island, who were usually huddled in and around Nathan's for warmth; I drew them while they regaled me with their stories. Some of those first sketches are included in this exhibit." Inspired by buzzing neon signs and accumulated layers of peeling paint, Spinelli began producing the wonderfully garish acrylic works featured in this exhibition.Unlike his drawings, his paintings are rendered from childhood memory rather than present experience. He states, "My paintings of Coney Island are vibrantly colored and thickly textured; I am painting not as I found it, but what I remember seeing in those fleeting images from the back window of that Delta 88 as we drove by." This exhibition is FREE and open to the public. For more information, visit nyc.gov/parks/art. A public opening reception will be held on Thursday, January 23, 2025, at 6 p.m. Image Credit: Christopher Spinelli, This Way to the Spookarama, 2021, acrylic paint, 36”x48”
category: Arsenal Gallery: Brooklyn Dreamland, Land without Shadows

events.name: Hart Island Tour (South Island)
events.description: Hart Island is the largest public cemetery in the country and has served New York City since 1869. Hart Island’s history is connected to many communities with important stories to tell. During the South Island Tour, Rangers will explore what Hart Island meant to the people who lived there, worked there, and were/are buried there. Walking the South Island includes discussion of an amusement park, military history, multiple pandemics, historic buildings and more. Join the Urban Park Rangers to hear their history and their voices.Participants are chosen by lottery. Lottery registration opens on Wednesday February 5, 2025 and ends Thursday February 6, 2025 at 11:59 p.m. Please Note:-You must register each member of your party for the lottery under the same account. Anyone who was not registered will not be permitted to attend.- If you are selected for the program, you will receive a series of emails confirming your selection and must respond as soon as possible to avoid forfeiting your spot. - Hart Island is only accessible via ferry. Selected participants will be provided details regarding program arrival and other specifics.- There are no indoor facilities, restrooms or drinking fountains on Hart Island. There are portable restrooms on the island.- This tour covers historical context of Hart Island and is about two hours of walking, some parts on uneven terrain. Please dress appropriately for the weather and the terrain.- Program may be cancelled due to inclement weather at the discretion of ferry operations.

events.name: Stream Big Book Launch
events.description:
Nathan Grayson, author of Stream Big: The Triumphs And Turmoils Of Twitch And The Stars Behind The Screen, is joined by Aftermath's Gita Jackson and Chris Person and Polygon's Simone de Rochefort for a discussion of the Amazon-owned livestreaming platform's place in modern gaming culture and beyond.
How did a website dedicated to watching people play video games grow into a force that has attracted attention from mainstream stars and politicians? What kind of work actually goes into being a popular Twitch streamer? Is it really as simple as sitting down in front of a camera and playing your favorite game? (No, absolutely not.) And how does one even begin to cover that as a journalist and write a book that encapsulates it all, especially when the world of livestreaming never stops, not even for a moment?
Come for answers to all of these questions and stay for never-before-told stories about your favorite/least favorite streamers.
rsvp

events.name: ONE DAY ONLY: Self-Help, PotCell, Golder on 3.13
events.description:
Self-help is a group with a singular brand of indie pop rock. Their explosive energy and infectious grooves bring audiences to life with a performance that is highly engaging and a sound that’s hard to pin down.
https://open.spotify.com/album/63IbJHpttefy5jEDzuLj3D?si=Bx-dHDcCRz68NRru6HFhmw
Powerhouse of The Cell began as a marketing experiment conducted by Keywrb Lab Group in the early 1990s. The goal was to create the illusion of a grassroots environmental movement through false flag TV and radio hijackings with music and visual art. While this project was ultimately defunded, there has recently been some documentation of the experiment resurfacing.
https://open.spotify.com/album/7aR08Te6AyMA65H8rBMvNl?si=r203_ZqqREiG2yI2TVnTEA
Golder is a noise pop artist who combines deep indie roots with explosive contemporary production. He’s based in NYC and plays live with Taj Searles and Jesse Zalk. He recently released his new EP, I’m So Shallow When I Think of Death, which harnesses the glistening chaos he explored in his earlier work and playfully tackles themes of consumerism and mortality.
https://open.spotify.com/album/11e3DbtUTbAv7IlhpveoEn?si=shJV7944TQu_DZn1EhHVJw

events.name: AnimeNEXT 2009: The Found Footage Documentary - 1st Public Screening!
events.description:
The anime con experience of yesteryear packed into a hot wild 80 minutes.
AnimeNEXT 2009: The Found Footage documentary aims to simply evoke the magic of the anime convention golden years via a preserved three day convention experience, nothing more nothing less.
Comprised entirely of old digi-cam footage from an era before everything was manicured for social media & the cell phone camera, the documentary throws you right into the con, forcing all to bask in awe of these bygone, earnest weebs; Heart filled to brim the power of friendship and anime, lacking any and all shame. Most people who've seen the film have laughed, many have cried, a few dubbed it incomprehensible, and one called it absolute dreck!
This is the first time the film will be screened to the public, will it bring you down memory lane or drive you to madness? In anime convention tradition, the documentary screening will be paired with a couple of classic anime con panels so get there early!: Anime Burger Time by Evan Minto (Azuki.co, Ani-Gamers) The Great Gundam Gebate, featuring a panel of Newtype Level Gundam Nerds. We encourage old cosplay and kigurumi's to this totally free event!
Hope you join us Sunday, March 16th from 2PM to 5PM!

events.name: GLHF! VGM and Digital Fusion Party
events.description:
A wild night of video game music, math rock, digital fusion and beyond. Join four new voices on the cutting edge of a new scene in Brooklyn.
GLHF - GLHF (Good Luck Have Fun) is a raucous party band specializing in fast-paced and layered synth-rock, jazz fusion, and hyperpop remixes of video game music, often mashed with music from anime and pop/internet culture. Led by Joe Etzine and featuring VGM giants including Dom Palombi, Khrys Williams, and others who have frequented the mainstages of Magfest and PAX East, GLHF is currently playing shows across the East Coast.
Visit
https://linktr.ee/jetzine
for clips and social media.
Maxo - Max Coburn, often under the name ‘Maxo’ is a musician and sound designer from Brooklyn, New York who specializes in digitally produced music, channelling a wide array of style and influence from Jazz, to Digital Fusion, to various types of dance music and beyond.
Visit
http://maxo.audio
Redddaz - is the spirit of Brooklyn in one man. This melting pot of American, Afro-Caribbean, and Afro-Latino cultures is not only the foundation of his music, but also his plane ticket to the rest of the world. Understanding that music ties us all together, this songwriter and producer seeks to bring a little piece of Brooklyn on his travels around the globe.
Visit
http://www.redddaz.com
Teal Jay - Fronted by Tyler Lee Jones, Teal Jay is a Brooklyn-based math rock project centered around their overhand guitar technique. They're influenced by artists in the NY/NJ indie emo/math punk and adjacent scenes (Invalids, Use Big Words, The Best of the Worst) as well as early 2000's J-rock/J-punk (STANE PUNKS, Sambomaster, AKFG).
Visit
linktr.ee/tylerleejones

events.name: Tackycardia: 2 Year Anniversary
events.description:
Well well well another year of Tackycardia in the books. Massive appreciation to everyone who has supported us over these last couple of years whether it’s artists we’ve booked, VJs, flyer designers, staff at Wonderville, or y’all who just serially show up and dance/game. We very much weren’t expecting for things to last this long when we started this little experiment out but here we are heading into year 3 of 150+ bpm fuckery!
Here’s what we’ve got for ya for our anniversary. Tackycardia alum DJ Allegation will be returning following appearances at Silo and Bossa Nova Civic Club. In addition, New England legend Jack McDevitt (also of Disco Ball Murder Kit) will be making the trek into NYC to treat us with some fresh sounds. Arpanette comes through following appearances at Eris and Café Kitsuné. Boj joins us following appearances at Happyfun Hideaway and the Cuff Complex while Tailz who heads Blast NYC comes following appearances at Eris, Trans Pecos and Hart Bar. The card will be rounded out by Tackycardia residents Cryostatik who recently put out 2 new tunes in Mess ‘Em Up and Solace as well as Alex Viper who is fresh off of December appearances at Tropical Dreams festival and Garage Sale in Massachusetts in addition to the Stuck on Earth reunion event in NYC. As usual not all of our lineup is known for their high BPM antics so we’re just as excited as y’all are to see what fantastic sets come out. Getting DJs and audiences alike a tad out of their comfort zones is one of our favorite things about doing these events and we are gonna keep it up :) Make sure to follow our instagram @tackcyardia_nyc as we’ll be posting a bit more about our artists in the lead up to the event!
We look forward to celebrating the occasion with y’all. As usual it’s a 150+ genrefluid affair with free entry and free to play arcade games. Donations are welcome to further support our events and can be made via cash in the tip bucket on the stage or via venmo through our QR code that you’ll see posted around the venue. Here’s to another year!
rsvp
